docs.chapter: Economic Models of Intellectual Property Governance for Generative AI
docs.para: First, what control does a human have in determining the creation of a generative artificial intelligence (AI) system that replicates their individual knowledge generation or “creative process,” and if such a system is created, what ownership claims or recourse does the human have? Second, what control does the “generator” of data have over its use in training such a generative AI system? Third, what claims might a human have over new works created by such a generative AI system? In this study, I contrast the answers to these questions suggested by current law with the answers that are provided by economic modeling of the social welfare maximizing outcomes

STAKEHOLDERS Impacted stakeholders Who is impacted by the system (e.g consumers, workers, government agencies)? OPTIONALITY Optionality and redress Can users opt out, e.g switch systems? Can users challenge or correct the output? HUMAN RIGHTS Human rights and democratic values Can the system’s outputs impact fundamental human rights (e.g human dignity, privacy, freedom of expression, non-discrimination, fair trial, remedy, safety)? WELL-BEING & ENVIRONMENT Well-being, society and the environment Can the system’s outputs impact areas of life related to well-being (e.g job quality, the environment, health, social interactions, civic engagement, education)? DISPLACEMENT {Displacement potential} Could the system automate tasks that are or were being executed by humans? ECONOMIC CONTEXT Criteria Description SECTOR Industrial sector Which industrial sector is the system deployed in (e.g finance, agriculture)? BUSINESS FUNCTION & MODEL Business function What business function(s) is the system employed in (e.g sales, customer service)? Business model Is the system a for-profit use, non-profit use or public service system? CRITICALITY Impacts critical functions / activities Would a disruption of the system’s function / activity affect essential services? SCALE & MATURITY Breadth of deployment Is the AI system deployment a pilot, narrow, broad or widespread? {Technical maturity} How technically mature is the system (Technology Readiness Level –TRL) DATA & INPUT Criteria Description COLLECTION Detection and collection Are the data and input collected by humans, automated sensors or both? Provenance of data and input Are the data and input from experts; provided, observed, synthetic or derived? Dynamic nature Are the data dynamic, static, dynamic updated from time to time or real-time? RIGHTS & IDENTIFIABILITY Rights Are the data proprietary, public or personal data (related to identifiable individual)? “Identifiability” of personal data If personal data, are they anonymised; pseudonymised? STRUCTURE & FORMAT {Structure of data and input} Are the data structured, semi-structured, complex structured or unstructured? {Format of data and metadata} Is the format of the data and metadata standardised or non-standardised? SCALE {Scale} What is the dataset’s scale? QUALITY AND APPROPRIATENESS {Data quality and appropriateness} Is the dataset fit for purpose? Is the sample size adequate? Is it representative and complete enough? How noisy are the data? AI MODEL Criteria Description MODEL CHARACTERISTICS Model information availability Is any information available about the system’s model? AI model type Is the model symbolic (human-generated rules), statistical (uses data) or hybrid? {Rights associated with model} Is the model open-source or proprietary, self or third-party managed? {Discriminative or generative} Is the model generative, discriminative or both? {Single or multiple model(s)} Is the system composed of one model or several interlinked models? MODEL-BUILDING Model-building from machine or human knowledge Does the system learn based on human-written rules, from data, through supervised learning, through reinforcement learning? Model evolution in the field ML Does the model evolve and / or acquire abilities from interacting with data in the field? Central or federated learning ML Is the model trained centrally or in a number of local servers or “edge” devices? MODEL INFERENCE {Model development / maintenance} Is the model universal, customisable or tailored to the AI actor’s data? {Deterministic and probabilistic} Is the model used in a deterministic or probabilistic manner? Transparency and explainability If information available to users to allow them to understand model outputs? TASK & OUTPUT Criteria Description TASKS Task(s) of the system What tasks does the system perform (e.g recognition, event detection, forecasting)? {Combining tasks and actions into composite systems} Does the system combine several tasks and actions (e.g content generation systems, autonomous systems, control systems)? ACTION Action autonomy How autonomous are the system’s actions and what role do humans play? APPLICATION AREA Core application area(s) Does the system belong to a core application area such as human language technologies, computer vision, automation and / or optimisation or robotics? EVALUATION {Evaluation methods} Are standards or methods available for evaluating system output? docs.para: More and more governments have been experimenting with artificial intelligence to optimize their service delivery and make better decisions

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: However, in the public sector, AI risks like bias and discrimination can have significant consequences on the lives of often millions of citizens

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Responsible AI principles like transparency and accountability (and concomitant AI risk management strategies) are therefore key to AI deployment in the public sector

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Such practices are essential to safeguard the rights of citizens in the digital age. Several risk management strategies are currently being deployed and tested throughout public organizations

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: One relatively recent strategy is an algorithm register, or a public database of all algorithms used by a government (or a specific government agency)

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: These registers also, at least in theory, elaborate on the purpose and scope of a specific algorithm, its technical details, and its impact on citizens’ fundamental rights

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: The registers are intended to improve public transparency and accountability on algorithm use by showing citizens how the algorithms deployed by the government may affect their lives, and to maintain a coherent overview of the digitalization and algorithmification of public governance

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: They have been tested, for instance, in the Netherlands and Finland. This policy brief focuses on some of the main issues of the “first generation” algorithm registers (based on our research on the Finnish and Dutch algorithm registers)

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Methodologically, we take a mixed-method qualitative approach by combining extant literature on public sector AI with a content analysis of the registers themselves and their project websites, and a two-track semi-structured interview approach, covering citizens affected by the algorithms in question and public servants who have experience with algorithm registers

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: In the coming weeks, we will enrich our data by discussing our drafted recommendations with public servants. Through our research, we identified four categories of shortcomings with the public algorithm register experiments: completeness, design, informativity, and accountability

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: We found, first, that many algorithm registers have a lot of empty fields, which naturally defeats the purpose of the registers in the first place

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Registers should be more than simply the names of algorithms being used

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Second, we found that their design is not intuitive, as a basic user experience (UX) interview approach revealed that some citizens may not always find the registers easy to navigate, which limits the effectiveness of the registers once again - although low sample size limitations apply here

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Third, the language used in the registers seems inaccessible and overly complex for non-experts, in particular for citizens with lower (digital) literacy

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Fourth, we found that the registers - in part due to their existing flaws - may not be very efficient at holding public organizations deploying AI accountable, especially if they are not maintained properly. Several broader consequences follow from these issues

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: We argue that there is a clear strategypurpose misalignment, as the way the registers are implemented and maintained (strategy) does not reflect their purpose of improving public transparency and better informing citizens of public algorithm use

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Furthermore, we contend that that algorithm registers should incentivize civil society organizations and individual citizens to exercise checks and balances on government automation and algorithmification - an objective that the registers currently arguably cannot fulfil due to the issues we identified

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: Lastly, the process of creating and deploying these registers should be iterative and continuous if they are to serve their main purpose: the registers and their designers need to engage in a feedback-based collaborative design process in order to better serve citizens. Our policy brief then offers actionable recommendations on how to resolve (or at least take a first step to mitigate) the issues and broader consequences outlined above

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: One key action point is building a culture of ownership and accountability within public service agencies

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: It is particularly important to improve accessibility for non-experts, as this opens redress possibilities for algorithm-driven injustices and rights infringements

docs.chapter: Empowering Citizens through Responsible AI Governance: Policy Recommendations for Public Algorithm Registers
docs.para: While recognizing the limitations of our approach (such as our Eurocentric research data, relatively low sample size, and limited access to internal processes behind the creation of the registers), we offer guidelines on how to turn algorithm registers from incomplete libraries for experts into a tool that facilitates administrative transparency and empowers citizens to hold governments accountable. docs.para: These drivers resulted in the local development of a chatbot, which heavily built on collecting training datasets with the local community of Kinyarwanda speakers.
